the core RNA polymerase (389 kDa; fraction 22), the deduced
molecular mass of the complexes eluted in fraction 26 was 169
kDa, which is larger than the expected molecular mass of the DnaK-␴32 complex (102 kDa). However, free DnaK (69 kDa) was
eluted in fraction 28, which corresponds to a deduced molecular mass of 107 kDa, and the only complexed ␴32 peak was present in
fractions 25 to 28. Therefore, we conclude that the complexes eluted in fraction 26 comprised one DnaK molecule and one ␴32
molecule. A similar phenomenon, in which free DnaK was eluted
in higher-molecular-weight fractions than in theory, was also ob-
served in a previous study (23). Next, to dissect the DnaK-␴32 interaction in the presence of
ATP, complexes formed in the presence of 0, 0.05, and 0.4 ␮M
DnaJ were analyzed by gel ﬁltration (Fig. 3). In the absence of DnaJ, ␴32 in complexes was detected in fractions 26 and 27. These

results are similar to those obtained in the presence of ADP (Fig. 2), though the amount of ␴32 in complexes was less than that detected in the presence of ADP. The amount of wild-type ␴32 in complexes was slightly larger than the amount of L201D ␴32 in
complexes. At 0.05 ␮M DnaJ, increased amounts of both wildtype and L201D ␴32 were detected in fraction 26. Because the concentration of DnaJ was lower than that of ␴32, this result indicates that DnaJ catalytically promotes the formation of DnaK-␴32 complexes. Intriguingly, a considerable amount of wild-type ␴32
was eluted in fractions 24 and 25, suggesting that another DnaK molecule bound to ␴32. Compared to that in the presence of 0.05 ␮M DnaJ, the amount of free ␴32 was much lower for both wildtype and mutant in the presence of 0.4 ␮M DnaJ, and ␴32 was
eluted in earlier fractions (fractions 22 to 25). This tendency was clearly observed for wild-type ␴32, and the molecular mass of the complexes containing wild-type ␴32 was larger than that of the

