ative) may affect its stability more markedly in KY1459 than in the wild-type strain. Similar results were obtained for L201D ␴32-His (Fig. 5A, B, D, and E and data not shown). At 40 ␮g/ml tryptophan, both wild-type and L201D ␴32-His were strongly stabilized, similar to I54A ␴32-His (Fig. 5F). This result indicates that the in vivo degradation of L201D ␴32-His was dependent on the DnaK chaperone system, even though the afﬁnity of L201D ␴32 for DnaK was reduced compared to that of wild-type ␴32. These ﬁndings suggest that ␴32 stability can be regulated by DnaK binding to any
one of multiple sites. DnaJ promotes DnaK binding to multiple sites on ␴32 in the
presence of ATP. Using the I54A ␴32-His and L201D ␴32-His mu-
tants, pulldown assays were performed to examine the effects of DnaJ on the DnaK-␴32 interaction under various conditions (Fig.
6). Regardless of the nucleotide used, the amounts of DnaK that coeluted with wild-type ␴32-His and I54A ␴32-His were compara-
ble in the absence of DnaJ, whereas much less DnaK was coeluted with L201D ␴32-His than with wild-type ␴32-His. This difference between wild-type ␴32 and L201D ␴32 was more clear than that
indicated by the gel ﬁltration analyses (Fig. 2 and 3), strongly suggesting that the region containing Leu201 is the primary target
site of DnaK in the absence of DnaJ. In the presence of DnaJ and ADP, the amounts of DnaK that coeluted with wild-type ␴32-His and L201D ␴32-His gradually increased with increasing DnaJ con-
centration, whereas the amount of DnaK that coeluted with I54A ␴32-His was not altered. Interestingly, in the presence of DnaJ and ATP, more DnaK was coeluted with L201D ␴32-His than with I54A ␴32-His, though the yield of DnaK was less than that obtained with wild-type ␴32-His. Because more DnaJ was coeluted with wild-type ␴32-His and L201D ␴32-His than with I54A ␴32His, these results indicate that DnaJ binding to ␴32 strongly en-
hances DnaK binding to sites that intrinsically exhibit a low afﬁn-
ity for DnaK, in addition to DnaK binding to the site containing Leu201.
DnaK binding to each site on ␴32 requires the hydrolysis of
DnaK-bound ATP through interactions with DnaJ. The results
described above demonstrate that multiple DnaK molecules simultaneously bind to ␴32 in the presence of ATP and DnaJ. Because the binding efﬁciency of DnaK to multiple sites on ␴32 was
low in the presence of ADP (Fig. 2 and 6), it is possible that some ATP-bound DnaK molecules bind to ␴32 without hydrolyzing
ATP. Therefore, it is important to examine whether the binding of multiple DnaK molecules to ␴32 requires the hydrolysis of ATP
bound to each DnaK.
First, we tested whether direct interactions between individual
DnaK molecules and DnaJ are required for DnaK binding to multiple sites on ␴32. DnaJ contains a speciﬁc domain known as the J
domain that is conserved among Hsp40 family proteins and includes the HPD motif, His33-Pro34-Asp35. DnaJ interacts with
DnaK through this HPD motif and promotes the ATPase activity
of DnaK, and amino acid substitutions in this motif result in weak binding of DnaK to substrates, such as ␴32 (22, 36). We con-
structed a dnaJ expression vector in which the histidine codon
(CAC) at position 33 was replaced with a glutamine codon (CAG). When the DnaJ-␴32 interaction was examined by pulldown assays, the amount of H33Q DnaJ that coeluted with ␴32-His was similar
to that of wild-type DnaJ (Fig. 7A), indicating that the H33Q mutation does not appreciably affect the DnaJ-␴32 interaction. However, when the DnaK-␴32 interaction was examined in the
presence of H33Q DnaJ and ATP, the amount of DnaK that coe-

